Getting started with the symbol interface

Mikkel Meyer Andersen and Søren Højsgaard

2019-08-05

Source: vignettes/symbol-interface.Rmd
symbol-interface.Rmd
library(Ryacas)

Introduction

Start with a base symbol what can either be:

  • A yacas command, e.g. x, 2*a or something similar
  • An R matrix or vector.

Here, we keep it simple. Consider an R matrix and vector:

A <- 2*diag(4)
A[1,2] <- 4
A[4,2] <- 2
diag(A)[2] <- 2
A
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    2    4    0    0
## [2,]    0    2    0    0
## [3,]    0    0    2    0
## [4,]    0    2    0    2
a <- 1:4
a
## [1] 1 2 3 4

They are now considered yacas-enabled:

B <- yac_symbol(A)
B
## {{2, 4, 0, 0},
##  {0, 2, 0, 0},
##  {0, 0, 2, 0},
##  {0, 2, 0, 2}}
b <- yac_symbol(a)
b
## [1] {1,2,3,4}

Notice how they are printed using yacas’s syntax.

Standard R commands are available:

  • [ (both extracting submatrices, rows, columns, subvectors etc. and assignment)
  • solve()
  • t()
  • +, -, *, /, %*%
  • diag()
  • upper.tri()
  • lower.tri()

See this brief demonstration:

There are additional functions available:

  • simplify()
  • tex()

To demonstrate these and some additional benefit, we exploit yacas’s symbolic availabilities.

D <- diag(4) %>% yac_symbol()
D <- D/"2" # "dividing" by string
D[2:3, 1] <- "d"
D[3,4] <- "2*d + 2"
D
## {{  1/2,     0,     0,     0},
##  {    d,   1/2,     0,     0},
##  {    d,     0,   1/2, 2*d+2},
##  {    0,     0,     0,   1/2}}
D %>% solve()
## {{           2,            0,            0,            0},
##  {      (-4)*d,            2,            0,            0},
##  {      (-4)*d,            0,            2, (-4)*(2*d+2)},
##  {           0,            0,            0,            2}}
D %>% solve() %>% simplify()
## {{         2,          0,          0,          0},
##  {    (-4)*d,          2,          0,          0},
##  {    (-4)*d,          0,          2, (-8)*(d+1)},
##  {         0,          0,          0,          2}}
D %>% solve() %>% simplify() %>% tex()
## [1] "\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc} 2 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\ -4 d & 2 & 0 & 0 \\\\ -4 d & 0 & 2 & -8 \\left( d + 1\\right)  \\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 2 \\end{array} \\right) "

\[ \left( \begin{array}{cccc} 2 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ -4 d & 2 & 0 & 0 \\ -4 d & 0 & 2 & -8 \left( d + 1\right) \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 2 \end{array} \right) \]

The function tex() is constructed using the helper function y_fn() that makes calls to yacas functions easier without lots of string concatenation:

tex(B)
## [1] "\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc} 2 & 1 & 1 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 2 & 1 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 0 & 2 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 2 & 0 & 2 \\end{array} \\right) "

yacas has a Simplify() function. This is made available via a simplify() function that also includes a time-out that prevents yacas in making the R session hang, but it requires that the unix package is available. The default timeout value used when unix is available is 2 seconds.
